IFB104: Building IT Systems

This unit provides a hands-on introduction to computer programming for students with no prior coding experience at all. It introduces the basic principles of programming in a typical imperative language, including expressions, assignment, functions, choice and iteration. It then shows how to use Application Programming Interfaces to complete common Information Technology tasks such as querying databases, creating user interfaces, and searching for patterns in large datasets. The emphasis is on developing skills through practice, so the unit includes numerous coding exercises and assignments, using a simple scripting language and code development environment. The unit establishes a foundation for later subjects that teach large-scale software development using industrial-strength programming languages.

Week 1: How to Evaluate Expressions

Types

Computers use types to distinguish what data we are parsing through the interpreter. There are many times but the main 3 we'll focus on are Strings, Integers and Floats.

An Integer can only hold whole numbers, a float can only hold decimals and a string can only hold text and the data must be encased in single or double quotes

print(3 + 4) # Add 2 integers
print(3.2 * 1.7) # Multiply two floats

$ 7
$ 5.44

We can use pythons built in .type() function to provide us information on what data type a value represents.

print(type(3 + 4))
print(type(3.2 * 1.7))

$ <class 'int'>
$ <class 'float'>

In python we can also tell the interpreter to convert an item into another data type (assuming the conversion is possible).

print(int(3.4 + 2.3)) # Convert the value of this equation into an integer
print(float(3 * 2)) # Convert the value of this equation into a float
print(round(1 / 3, 2)) # Round the value of this expression (1/3) to 2 decimal places

$ 5 
$ 6.0
$ 0.33

Variables

Variables allow us to store the value of an expression that we can reference later by using a name we denote to the variable. In python this is as simple as saying

price = 13 # Create a variable with the name price and assign it the value 13
howMany = 7
total = howMany * price # Create a variable with the name total and assign it the value of the expression (howMany * price)
print(f'You owe {total} dollars') 

$ 'You owe 91 dollars'

*note: python variable names may never start with an integer or symbol

With variables comes the ability of string splicing. Variables that hold strings are really just holding a collection of characters which are put together to create a single item. We can retrieve these individual characters in a string using string splicing.

*note: always remember computers start counting from 0, although the first item in a list looks like item 1 it is actually item 0

firstWord = 'Hello'

print(firstWord[0])
print(firstWord[2] + firstWord[4] + firstWord[3])

$ 'H'
$ 'lol'

Python also includes ways to manipulate text using special characters preceded by a \

print('Hello\nWorld') # \n denotes everything writen after it must procede on the next line
print('Hello\tWorld') # \t replicates a tab (inserts 4 spaces)

$ 'Hello'
$ 'World'
$ 'Hello    World'

Lists

Lists are a way to create collections of items regardless of the data type and much like strings can be manipulated to return certain items from different indexed positions. There are many more things we can do with lists but these will be discussed later.

lottoNumbers = [2, 10, 19, 34, 40, 42]
print(f'The third lotto number is {lottoNumbers[2}')
print(lottoNumbers[0] + lottoNumbers[-1]) #By using -1 we can specify we want to count this list backwards (when counting backwards we start at 1)

$ 'The third lotto number is 19'
$ 44

Week 2: How to use predefined functions

Functions

A function is a like a variable except instead of providing a value we're providing it a set of instructions and just like how we can call variables we can also call these functions. Some functions have arguments we need to provide to them, this is done by adding our data between the ().

oak = 8
larch = 21
poplar = 7
biggest = max(poplar, larch, oak)
print(f'The tallest tree is {biggest} metres high')

$ 'The tallest tree is 21 metres high'

Methods

Methods are like functions however are only applicable to certain types. These types are formatted slightly different with the data you want to the method to take effect on coming first then proceeded with a .method_name().

myName = 'Samantha'
myName.find('ant')

$ 3

Character String Operations

Here are a couple more things we can do to manipulate strings using string indexing and other methods/functions.

phrase = 'Hello there, World!!'

print(len(phrase)) # Will return the length of the string
print(phrase.replace('Hello', 'Goodbye')) # replace substring
print(phrase[1]) # Get the character at position 1
print(phrase[6:11]) # Return substring from position 6 upto 11
print(phrase.split()) # Split the string by spaces and return a list of each split item
print(phrase.strip('!')) # Remove leading/trailing characters

$ 21
$ 'Goodbye there, World!!'
$ 'e'
$ 'there'
$ ['Hello', 'there', 'World!!']
$ 'Hello there, World'

More with Lists

There are so many things we can do to manipulate lists, here are a couple more examples of things we can do.

colours = ['red', 'green', 'blue']

print(colours.index('blue')) # Returns the index value of 'blue' in our list
print(colours.count('blue')) # Return the amount of times 'blue' shows up in our list
colours.append('purple') # Add the value 'purple' to our list
print(colours)

colours[1] = 'orange' # Replace the value at index position 1 with the new value 'orange'
print(colours)

colours.insert(2, 'white') # Insert a new value at index position 2
print(colours)

$ 2
$ 1
$ ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'purple']
$ ['red', 'orange', 'blue', 'purple']
$ ['red', 'orange', 'white', 'blue', 'purple']

Random Numbers

There are many things that we can do in python but not all of these things are possible using the base python libraries, to extend pythons ability we import modules. The module `random` allows us to create random numbers easily by using the modules pre-defined methods and functions.

import random # We declare what modules we want to use by using import + the module name

options = ['a', 'b', 'c']

print(randint(3, 9)) # Choose a random number between 3 and 9
print(randint(3, 9))
print(choice(options)) # Choose a random value from the list
print(choice(options))

$ 3
$ 5
$ 'c'
$ 'b'

Looping

There are many ways we can loop code in python, one of the simple ways is with a for loop. For loops repeat actions a specified amount of times.

for word in range(5)  
    print('Hello')
    
$ 'Hello'
$ 'Hello'
$ 'Hello'
$ 'Hello'
$ 'Hello'

We can also use loops as a value for the amount of times we want to iterate

winds = ['N', 'S', 'E', 'W']

for wind in winds:
    print("Whoosh!")

$ 'Whoosh!'
$ 'Whoosh!'
$ 'Whoosh!'
$ 'Whoosh!'

Graphics with the turtle module

A commonly used module designed for drawing onto a canvas is the `turtle` module. With the turtle module we can design and draw shapes onto a canvas to create drawings or UI elements. By using a combination of previously taught skills lets draw a star using the turtle library.

from turtle import * # Here we specify what parts we want from the turtle library with * specifying we want all parts of it

setup() # Telling turtle we want to draw something
pendown()
for actions in range(5) # Draw the points of the star
    forward(150)
    right(144)

hideturtle() # Hide the graphical turtle
done() # Tell python we're done with this drawing

Week 3: How to create reusable code

Functions

We've already seen on how to use a function but how can we create one ourselves? By creating functions we can write repetitive code once and assign that set of tasks to a variable name and call it back when we need.

from math import tan, radians

# Here we create a function named height that takes in 2 parameters (distance and angle)
# and returns a single value
def height(distance, angle): 
    heightOfObject = round(distance * tan(radians(angle)))
    return heightOfObject # This is the value returned from the function
    
distanceToTree = 75
angleToTop = 40
print(f'The tree is {height(distanceToTree, angleToTop} feet high')

$ 'The tree is 63 feet high'

Functions don't always have to have parameters however when we do use them we can define default parameters to values we expect.

def power(base, exponent=2):
    return base ** exponent
    
print(power(4))
print(power(4, 3))

$ 16
$ 64

Here we can see that because we specified exponent to have a default value we dont have to give it a value when calling. However, if we want to we can simply overwrite that default by adding the value in our call statement.

Variable Scope

All variables in python are given a scope upon creation, these consist of local and global. Any variable inside of a function is considered to be part of that local scope meaning it cannot be called or referenced outside of that local scope (i.e. the function). Any variable created outside of a function (i.e. the main body of the file) is considered to have a global scope and can be referenced anywhere in the file (even inside functions).

Variable/Function Names

As said earlier when naming variables and functions there are a few rules we need to keep in mind. The first rule to note is names can never start with an integer or float or symbol of any kind, they must always start with a letter. Another thing to keep in mind is that python already has pre-defined functions which already have names we cant used. This means we cant use certain names for our variables and functions including

  • Statement keywords such as for, def, return, etc

  • Built-in function names such as range, max, len, etc

  • Standard module names such as math, turtle, etc

Commenting

As you have probably seen throughout the code examples so far there have been statements of text the python interpreter has been avoiding, these are called comments. Comments allow us to write human readable text that's ignored by python upon running the file. There are a few ways of commenting code such as the # symbol (# Hash comment), or even surrounding your comment in triple quotes ('''Triple quote comment''')

Week 4: How to make decisions

Boolean Expressions

The boolean data type can only contain 2 values, True or False. Many conditionals will return a boolean based on the conditions given. Another thing to note is the difference between '=' and '=='. The single equals sign is used when assigning something to a variable, double equals sign is used when comparing or testing for equality.

weight = 64
print(weight == 64)
print(57 == weight)

$ True
$ False

User Input

One reason for needing to make choices it due to possible inputs from an external source, the user. The simplest form of input is direct input from the terminal and this can be grabbed using a simple input() statement.

response = input('Please enter an expression: ') # Grab the user input and store it in a variable
print(f'You typed "{response}"')
print(f'Your expression equals {eval(response)}')

$ Please enter an expression: 6 * 7.2
$ You typed '6 * 7.2'
$ Your expression equals 43.2

Conditional Statements

The most basic conditional statement in python is the if statement.

  • A single-alternative if statement

  • A two-alternative if-else statement

  • A many-alternative if-elif-else statement

Example of an if statement:

normalPay = hoursWorked * payRate
overtimePay = 0

if hoursWorked > 40:
    overtimeHours = hoursWorked - 40
    overtimePay = overtimeHours * payRate * 0.5
    
pay = normalPay + overtimePay

Example of an if-else statement:

from turtle import *

goto(0, -100)
setheading(90)

for step in range(30):
    if ycor() >= 0:
        pencolor('blue')
    else:
        pencolor('red')
    
    forward(20)

Example of an if-elif-else statement: (... used to state previous code is needed but not shown)

...
if speed < 5:
    print('Hurry up')
elif speed < 50:
    print('Go a bit quicker')
elif speed < 90:
    print('That's fast enough')
else:
    print('Slow down')

We can also nest if functions inside of each other to create nested conditional statements.

...
if salary >= 30000:
    if yearsInJob >= 2:
        print('You qualify for the loan')
    else:
        print('You must have worked in your current job for at least 2 years first')
else:
    print('You must earn at least $30,000 to qualify for a loan')

Week 5: How to repeat actions

Fixed Iteration

Using for loops we've already seen we can loop through values and repeat an action a certain amount of times. Using for loops we can also refer to each of the values in another value (i.e. each character in a string or each value in a list)

for letter in 'WHAM':
    print(letter)
    
$ 'W'
$ 'H'
$ 'A'
$ 'M'

This as mentioned before can also be used for items in an array.

numbers = [45, 6, 23, 12, 9, 3, 25]

for number in numbers:
    if number < 10:
        print(number)
	
$ 6
$ 9
$ 3

Reading data from files

In python we can read data from files and manipulate this data using loops.

textFile = open('words.txt')
for line in textFile:
    print(line)

Lists of lists

Using lists we can store even more lists creating a list of lists. This is a simple way for sorting data sets into categories.

elements = [
    # Inert gases
    ['He', 'Ne', 'Ar', 'Kr', 'Xe'],
    # Halogens
    ['F', 'Cl', 'Br', 'I', 'At'],
    # Alkili earth metals
    ['Li', 'Na', 'K', 'Rb', 'Cs']
]

for family in elements:
    for symbol in family:
        if 'a' in symbol.lower():
	    print(symbol)
	    
$ 'Ar'
$ 'At'
$ 'Na'

Condition-controlled Iteration

For a for loop to work we must have a clear idea of how many times we need to iterate but lets assume we don't know how many times we want the program to loop, this is why we use while loops. While loops allow us to keep looping until a certain condition is met.

number = 5
sum = 0

while (sum < number):
    print(sum)
    sum += 1 # This is the same as saying `sum = sum + 1`
    
$ 0
$ 1
$ 2
$ 3
$ 4

It must be aware that you can create infinite loops so you must be careful when setting them up.

natural = 0

# This is an infinite loop
while (natural >= 0):
    print(natural)
    if natural < 10:
        natural += 1

Recursive Functions

Another way we can perform actions repeatedly is to define recursive functions. Recursion simply involves functions that call themselves.

def countdown(time):
    if time == 0:
        print('Lift off!')
    else:
        print(time)
	countdown(time - 1)
	
countdown(5)

$ 5
$ 4
$ 3
$ 2
$ 1
$ 'Lift off!'

Recursive function definitions always involve at least one base case and one recursive case

  • A base case returns an answer straight away

  • A recursive case does one step of the calculation and relies on recursion to solve the remainder

def collectCaps(text):
    if text == '': # Base case
        return ''
    elif text[0].isupper(): # Recursive case
        return text[0] + collectCaps(text1[1:])
    else: # Recursive case
        return collectCaps(text[1:])

collectCaps('International Business Machines')

$ 'IBM'

Much like infinite loops, infinite recursion can happen. Whenever creating loops you must always make sure there is a way for your loops to end.

Week 6: How to interact with the user

Python GUI with Tkinter

Tkinter is an API for accessing the 'Tk' GUI functions providing us with the ability to create GUI's for our applications. This guide will give a brief rundown, for a more in-depth tutorial this here is not too shabby (also written by me)

from tkinter import *

root = Tk() # Create a GUI window

myButton = Button(root, text='Push me') # Create a button
myButton.pack() # Pack the button onto the GUI screen

root.mainloop() # Wait for the user to do something

Changing the User Interface

There are many ways we can change this GUI and create it to our liking.

from tkinter import *

root = Tk()

root.geometry('200x50') # Set the windows size
root['bg'] = 'red' # Set the windows background to red

myButton = Button(root, text='Push me', highlightbackground = 'red')
myButton.pack(pady = 10)

root.mainloop()

Communication between Widgets

Some widgets, e.g. Buttons and Spinboxes, have a command property which can be linked to functions which get called when the widget is activated. Other text based widgets have methods which allow you to change their state from other functions.

Week 7: How to format web documents

HTML

HTML is a markup language used to design webpages for websites. HTML uses markup tags to categories various elements in the document. HTML tags are keywords surrounded by angled brackets usually coming with a start and end pair, the end pair consisting of a / before the tag keyword.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head>
	<title>My Webpage</title>
    </head>
    <body>
	<h1>Heading 1</h1>
	<p>This is a paragraph tag</p>
    </body>
</html>

Here are some common HTML elements that can be found in a document body

<!-- Headings (from largest to smallest) -->
<h1>...</h1>
<!-- All the way to -->
<h6>...</h6>

<p>This is a paragraph</p>

<br /> <!-- This is a line break -->
<a href='#'>This is a hyperlink</a>
<img src='' width='' height='' alt=''> <!-- This is an image -->

<ul> <!-- Unordered List -->
    <li>This is an item in a list</li>
</ul>

<table>
    <caption>This is a table</caption>
    <tr> <!-- Table row -->
        <th>This is a table header</th>
	<td>This is table data</td>
    </tr>
</table>

CSS

CSS is a way to style elements in a HTML document. There are 3 ways we can style an element, inline styling, inline style sheet, external style sheet.

...
<style> <!-- This is an inline style sheet
    body {
	background-color: lightyellow
    }
</style>

<!-- This is inline styling  -->
<h1 style='text-align: center'>Weird aircraft</h1>

CSS external styling sheets are kept in another file but accept normal CSS formatting

body {
    background-color: lightyellow
}

Manipulating Web Documents with Python

Due to HTML files really just being fancy text documents we can download them and manipulating them using python functions. Pythons urllib module allows us to read webpages as sequences of text.

from urllib.request import urlopen

url = 'http://www.wikipedia.org/'

webPage = urlopen(url)
# Convert the file to unicode characters
webDocContents = webPage.read().decode('UTF-8')

Writing to Text Files

We saw earlier how we could open text files but we can also write data to these text files using the .write() method.

# Open the text file in 'write' mode
textFile = open('document.txt', 'w', encoding = 'UTF-8')

for number in range(100):
    textFile.write(f'{str(number)}\n') # Write each string with a newline character at the end

textFile.close() # Close the file

Week 8: How to find things

Finding Text Patterns in Character Strings

Using pythons inbuilt .find() method we can find sub-strings hidden away in other strings.

tongueTwister = 'The sixth sick sheik's sixth sheep's sick'
print(tongueTwister.find('sick')) # Returns the index position of the first match
print(tongueTwister.rfind('sick')) # Returns the index position of the last match

$ 10
$ 37

Using a simple for loop we can find all the occurrences of said sub-string

tongueTwister = 'The sixth sick sheik\'s sixth sheep\'s sick'
position = tongueTwister.find('si')

while position != -1: # .find() returns -1 if the searched item doesn't exist 
    print(f'"si" appears at position {position}')
    position = tongueTwister.find('si', position + 1)

$ '"si" appears at position 4'
$ '"si" appears at position 10'
$ '"si" appears at position 23'
$ '"si" appears at position 37'

Regular Expression with Regex

Regular expressions are a way to search for specific data in intricate strings of data. We can use these to find patterns in our python strings.

from re import findall
numbers = 'The decimal number 185 is the same as hexadecimal number 89 and octal number 271'

print(findall('m[aeiou]', numbers))
print(findall('[0-9A-F]+', numbers))
print(findall('[a-z]*x[a-z]*', numbers))

$ ['ma', 'me', 'ma']
$ ['185', 'B9', '271']
$ ['hexadecimal']

Regex is some what complicated with how many special characters there are and how they all interact with each other. Here is a great resource to learn more about them and how they work with python.

Week 9: How to remember things

Databases

A database is collection of logically related and sorted data allowing us to store data permanently unlike storing data in a list where when the program restarts all that data is reset/lost. To view the stored data in a database we must use a database management system, for this course we are using SQLite and DB Browser. We use the SQL language to modify and interact with the data inside of our database.

...
/* Add one of Wonder Woman's enemies */
INSERT INTO enemies VALUES ('Baroness Paula von Gunther', 'Wonder Woman');

/* Add another of Batman's vulnerabilities */
INSERT INTO vulnerabilities(superhero, weakness) VALUES ('Batman', 'Bombs');

/* Update Dr. Sivana's name */
UPDATE enemies SET enemy = 'Dr. Thaddeus Sivana' WHERE enemy LIKE '%Sivana%';

/* Delete actors who played superheroes in the 1950s */
DELETE FROM actors WHERE years LIKE '195%';

/* Retrieve a single column, sorted alphabetically, and with no duplicates */
SELECT DISTINCT enemy 
FROM enemies 
ORDER BY enemy;

We can use python to manipulate this data in a database using the sqlite3 module.

from sqlite3 import *

conn = connect('superheroes.db')
conn.execute('''SELECT superhero, secret_identity
		FROM identities
		ORDER BY superhero ASC''')
		
for hero, identity in conn.fetchall():
    print(f'{hero} ({identity}))

conn.close()

Week 10: How to prevent programs crashing

Defensive Programing

Defensive programming is all about doing whatever we can to stop the program from crashing. This can be done in a couple ways such as using if conditions to check for specific type answers or by running items in a try except block.

# Sanity check: Air pressure cannot be a negative
if barometerReading < 0:
    print("error")

# Try this code, if an error appears, run the code in the except statement
try:
    print(2 * 3)
except:
    print(2 * 5)

Week 11: How to build an IT system

A Classic Plan-driven Waterfall

  • Requirements Elicitation: The first step is finding out what the client requires

  • A Rapid Prototype: To help confirm the requirements, a crude prototype can be built using existing software

  • A Project Plan:

    • Divide up the work based on the teams expertise

    • Define the front-end/back-end interface

  • Mocking up the GUI: Mock functions simulate code that hasn't been written yet, or resources outside your system that don't yet exist

  • Testing the Back-end Functions: Purely functional parts of the program, with no user interaction, can be developed alongside their automated user tests

  • Integration Testing: Integrate the front-end with the back-end and test the results

  • Adding Robustness: Integrate a way to prevent unexpected inputs and results

  • Polishing the GUI: Add the final touches and functionality to the GUI

  • Final Touches and Deployment: Finish the app and deploy it to the client

Week 12: How to do cool things

Conditional Expressions

Conditional statements are great when it comes to multiple values needing to be check but when we are just aiming to get a boolean based answer we can use conditional expressions instead. These allow us to do the same thing in much less code.

temperature = -3

if temperature < 0:
    result = 'Cold'
else:
    result = 'Hot'
    
print(result)

answer = 'Cold' if temperature < 0 else 'Hot'
print(answer)

$ 'Cold'
$ 'Cold'

List Builders

Often times we use loops to create our lists one value at a time however using list builders we can do the exact same in less code.

palindrome = 'Nurses run!'

nonConsonants = []
for char in palindrome:
    if char in 'aeiou':
        nonConsonants.append(char)

print(nonConsonants)

vowels = [char for char in palindrome if char in 'aeiou']
print(vowels)

$ ['u', 'e', 'u']
$ ['u', 'e', 'u']
